s derived  along generally linear traverses that extended southeastward from the Wabash  River Valley (Caldwell and White, 1956; Frazee et al., 1970; Hall, 1973).  Loess thickness distribution, however, is more complicated in that area. Loess-  thickness contours have a parabolic distribution with one limb of the parabola  paralleling the Wabash River Valley and the other limb paralleling the Ohio  River Valley (Fehrenbacher et al., 1965). The parabolic distribution fits be-  tween the confluent riverine systems.  Clay-mineral composition, as a source indicator of loess, was added to the    *1Present address: U.S. Geological Survey, Menlo Park, Calif., U.S.A.    284    RU    IV  B  CH     HAUTE     ,NO,AN pOL,S / C  /           E-,~.    =o    0    l/  ~MADISON  M ,,~..---~  /    NEW ALBANY    T     ~.~ k,,,,~.~ Omi          44)                                 I     I    ii     t    J  -1 '    '  ' 66    Fig. 1. Locations of stratigraphic sections in southern Indiana are indicated by letter  symbols. Symbols are identified in text.    loess&lt;listribution model in !Uinois (Glass et al., 1968), but there changes in  composition, mainly contents of illite and expandable clay minerals, are  attributed to modifications in major drainage lines caused by Pleistocene  glacial diversions (Frye et al., 1968). These charges in glacial source materials  resulted in a stratigraphic clay-mineral zoning in the later Wisco~ loess  near the source area (Frye et al., 1968)and along traverses downwind from  the source area (Kleiss, 1973).  The dual riverine source system in Indiana differs from that of Illinois.  The Wabash River is the western boundary of southern Indiana, and the Ohio  River is the southern bound~ (Fig. 1). The Wabash River drainage basin has  an area of 87,300 km2 (33,100 sq. mi.). Wisconsinan gl~ial driR covers  47,400 km2 (18,300 sq. mi.). Illinoian glacial drift mantles 32,375 km2  (12,500 sq. mi.). Nongiacial terrain south of the Hlinoian drift border occu-    285    pies 7,380 km2 (2,850 sq. mi.) in southern Indiana (Fig. 1). The bedrock in  this reentrant is Mississippian and Pennsylvanian carbonate and clastic rocks  including coal measures. Thus, about 91% of the Wabash River drainage basin  is covered with glacial drift, and the major valleys carried the glacial outwash  and alluvium that provided source material for loess.  The Ohio River drainage basin differs radically. Its area is about 261,500  km2 (101,000 sq. mi.) above the mouth of the Wabash River. Wisconsinan  drift covers only 46,880 km~ (18,100 sq. mi.}, and Illinoian drift covers only  13,440 km2 (5,190 sq. mi.). The major part of the drainage basin {77%) is  nonglacial, and the bedrock is Paleozoic carbonate and clastic rocks including  coal measures. The soils in the nonglacial terrain range from Inceptisols to  Alfisols and to Ultisols. Thus, not only was glacial outwash ultimately carried  by the Ohio River from 23% of its drainage basin, but alluvium derived from  erosion of the soils and bedrock also was carried by the Ohio River from 77%  of its drainage basin and along the southern boundary of Indiana.  The question arises: does the mineralogy of the loess derived from the  Wabash Valley of dominantly glacial origin differ from the mineralogy of the  loess derived from the Ohio Valley which may be dominantly of nonglacial  origin? This problem is approached by determining the clay-mineral composi-  tion of stratigraphic sections of loess in both provinces (Fig. 1).  Quantitative estimates of kaolinite (K, 7.2 A }, illite (I, 10 A ), and expand-  able clay minerals (X, 14--17 A ) were made by using the method of additions  of proportions of soil clay to a constant standard (Ruhe and Olson, 1979).  The reference standard is a 1:1:1 mix by weight of the ~2 ~m fractions of  kaolinite KGA-1 and montmorillonite TX-1 (Clay Minerals Society standards)  and a reference illite from the Blaylock Formation, Oklahoma (Mankin and  Dodd, 1963 }. In the study reported here, new prediction equations for  estimating K%, I%, and X% are based on experimental mixes of 31 samples  selected from the total array of samples. The prediction equations are:  K (%) = --2.67 + 70.88 Ki, where R2 = 0.92 and Se = + 3%  In I (%) = In 104.61 + 0.67 In Ii, where R2 = 0.96 and Se = + 6%  X (%) = -0.26 + 92.1 Xi, where R2 = 0.88 and Se = +- 6%  and where Ki, Ii, and Xi are intensity ratios calculated from X-ray powder  diffraction patterns. The R2 values give the proportions of the total estimate  that are explained by the prediction equations. The Se values are the statis-  tical standard errors of estimate.  Within the expandable clay mir~erals, vermiculite (14 A ) and montmoril-  lonite (17 A ) are reported as proportions or parts of 100. In this paper the  symbols K, I, X, and 14 A will be used to avoid incessant repetition of min-  eral-group names.    WISCONSINAN LOESSES    Two Wisconsinan loesses are in southern Indiana (Ruhe, 1976). An upper  Peoria loess is the thicker one, is yellowish brown or gray, and near a source    286    area may be calcareous. In areas where the loess is thinner, it is noncalcareous.  Peoria loess buries a Farmdale loess, and the latter is distinguished by  brown and reddish-brown color and by the presence at places of organic  matter. It is universally noncalcareous although it may be secondarily en-  riched with carbonate where overlain by calcareous Peoria loess. The Farm-  dale loess, where prominent, is readily distinguished from the overlying Peoria  loess (Fehrenbacher et al., 1965; Ruhe, 1976). Farmdale loess or its strati-  graphic equivalent has been identified in the Wabash Basin from Russellville  and Fillmore (Fig. 1, R U, F), where it is buried beneath Wisconsinan glacial  till, down the Wabash Valley to Mount Vernon (Fig. 1, MV). It has been  identified up the Ohio Valley to Troy (Fig. 1, T). Where buried beneath  Peoria loess in these sections, the Peoria loess is 10 to &gt; 50 times thicker than  the Farmdale loess.  The chronology of the Wisconsinan loesses is demonstrated in the strati-  graphic correlation of the group of sections northeast of Terre Haute (Fig. 1).  At RusseUville (R U), an organic silt 70 cm thick contains coniferous wood  and is buried beneath 6.8 m of early Wisconsinan-glacial till. The silt, in turn,  overlies the Bb horizon of the Sangamon Soil formed in Illinoian till. Soft-  horizon nomenclature follows the Soil Survey Staff (Supp., 1962). A wood  sample from the silt is radiocarbon dated at 20,110 -+ 360 years (ISGS-475).  At Fillmore (F) a stratigraphically equivalent organic silt 5 cm thick is buried  beneath early Wisconsinan glacial till and again overlies the Bb horizon of  the Sangamon Soil formed in Illinoian till. A coniferous wood sample at the  contact of the upper till and the organic silt is 20,660 +- 180 years old {ISGS-  541).  At a site in Parke County in front of the Wisconsinan drift border (Fig. 1,  PK), a peat 90 cm thick is buried beneath 3.65 m of Peoria loess and the  peat in turn buries the Bb horizon of the Sangamon Soil formed in Illinoian  till. Conferous wood fragments from mid&lt;lepth of the peat are 23,700 +-  1000 years old (W-4212). Nearby at a site in Vigo County (V) a peaty organ-  ic Ob horizon 15 cm thick is buried beneath 3.6 m of Peoria loess and in  turn overlies 1.4 m of gleyed muck, Cgb horizon. The muck buries the Bb  horizon of the Sangamon Soil in IUinoian till. Coniferous wood from the Ob  horizon is 22,700 + 500 years old (W4215).  At Brazil (Fig. 1, B) a silty organic Alb horizon 28 cm thick is buried  beneath 1.15 m of Peoria loess and overlies the Bb horizon of the Sangamon  Soil formed in Illinoian drift. Because of shallow burial and possible con-  tamination, humic acids were extracted from the organic carbon of a sample  of the Alb horizon. The radiocarbon date of the humin (residue) is 25,480 +  420 years, and the date of the humic-acid extract is 23,690 + 980 years and in  reasonable agreement age-wise.  These radiocarbon dates range from 20,100 to 25,500 years and fit within  the time-transgressive span of the Farmdale Soil (Ruhe, 1976). They date the  Farmdale loess and equivalent deposits and also give the maximum ages for  the Peoria loess and early Wisconsinan till. This stratigraphic framework    287    provides the basis for examining the loesses on the Illinoian drift plain and in  the nonglacial area of southern Indiana (Fig. 1). Specific stratigraphic sections  will be analyzed within the Wabash Valley province and in the Ohio Valley  province.    WABASH VALLEY PROVINCE    New Harmoney section (Fig. 1, NH)    This section is a road cut in the bluffs bordering the Wabash River Valley.  Peoria loess is 10.4 m thick. The upper 8 m are yellowish brown, calcareous  and fossiliferous. This zone is termed oxidized loess. The lower 2.4 m are  gray, with reddish brown, iron-oxide mottles and pipestems, and calcareous.  This zone is termed deoxidized loess (Ruhe, 1969). Beneath this zone is  brown, noncalcareous Farmdale loess that is 0.7 m thick. The Farmdale loess  rests on the Sangamon Soil formed in Illinoian till.  The Peoria loess has very uniform clay (&lt;2 ~m), fine silt (2--16 t~m), coarse  silt (16--62 pm), sand (&gt;62 pm), and CaCO3 contents throughout its thick-  ness (Fig. 2). Clay and fine silt abruptly increase and coarse silt and CaCO3  abruptly decrease in the Farmdale loess. The mean clay-mineral composition  of the Peoria loess is kaolinite or K, 16 + 2.8%; illite or I, 57 + 3.7%; and ex-  pandable clay minerals or X, 30 -+ 4.0%. The sum of the means is 103%, but  the standard deviations compensate for the excessive sum. Such compensation  applies to all mean compositions reported in this paper. The mean clay-  mineral composition of the Farmdale loess is K, 13 + 1.0%; I, 19 -+ 1.0%; and    P  OU  P  du  F  SB    CaCO5 o  0%    20         40        60         80       1(30     0%     20         40         60   