I, 30 + 9.0%; and X, 48 + 12%. This composition differs from Peoria loess of  the Wabash province (Tables I, II) but does not differ significantly from the  composition of the Peoria loess of the Ohio province. In this last pairing the  t values for I and X fall within the t value for the 95% confidence limit, and  the value for K only slightly exceeds the critical value.  In order to determine the possible source materials for clay-mineral com-  ponents of Peoria loess and Farmdale loess, comparisons are made between  the compositions of these loesses and the other materials with which they are  associated in the field. On the basis of all samples, Peoria loess is successively  compared to Farmdale loess, to the Sangamon Soil B horizon formed in  glacial till, to the Sangamon Soil B horizon formed in bedrock, and to the  glacial till. The Farmdale loess is similarly analyzed. Other pairings also are  tested (Tables I, II). Within this analytical array, three relations emerge. The  clay-mineral compositions of the Peoria loess and glacial tills in the Wabash  province are similar in major components. There are no statistically significant  differences between paired K, I, or X (Table II). Glacial sediments are the  dominant source materials for the clay-mineral composition of the Peoria  loess in the thicker loess belt. As noted in the introduction about 91% of the  Wabash Basin is covered with glacial drift.    296    A second relation is the similarity in part of the composition of Farmdale  loess and the Sangamon Soil B horizon formed in bedrock. If the 14 A com-  ponent is included in the analysis, then two of four of the clay-mineral com-  ponents do not differ statistically, I and 14 A. A third relation is the similar-  ity of compositions of Peoria loess of the Ohio province and the Farmdale  loess. There are no significant differences in the I and X components, and the  t-value of K only slightly exceeds the value at the 95% confidence limit  {Table II).  The upward continuity of clay-mineral composition from the paleosol into  overlying Farmdale loess and even the Peoria.loess was discussed previously  for the Bayou Creek, Cumback, and Troy sections where the Paleosol is  formed in bedrock. In general, the Wisconsinan loess is thinner in the bedrock  region and throughout the Ohio province. The impact of source materials  from the paleosol terrain on bedrock probably accounts for similarity in part  of clay-mineral composition of paleosol to Farmdale loess and in turn to  Peoria loess in the Ohio province. As noted in the introduction, about 77% of  the Ohio Basin is nonglacial terrain. Alluvium derived from erosion of that  terrain was carried by the Ohio River during Farmdalian and Peorian times.  Debris deposited along the valley could have been the source for loess onto  the uplands.    ACKNOWLEDGEMENTS    Elizabeth Matney did the X-ray powder diffraction work in the laboratory.  Parts of the field studies were done in Quaternary geology with H.H. Gray  and N.K. Bleuer, indiana Geological Survey and in soils with A.K. NickeU  and K.M. McWilliams, Soil Conservation Service, U.S. Department of Agricul-  ture. Radiocarbon dating was provided by M. Rubin, U.S. Geological Survey  (W&lt;lates) and D.D. Coleman, Illinois Geological Survey (ISGS~lates). Their  cooperative work is appreciated.    REFERENCES    Caldwell, R.E. and White, J.L., 1956. A study of the origin and distribution of loess in  southern Indiana. Soll Sci. Soc. Am. Proc., 20: 258--263.  Daniels, R.B., Handy, R.L. and Simormon, G.H., 1960. Dark-colored bands in the thick  loess of Western Iowa. J. Geol., 68: 450--458~  Fehrenbacher, J.B., White, J.L., Ulrich, H.P. and Ode]/, R.T., 1965. Loess distribution in  southeastern Illinois and southwestern Indiana. Soil Sci. Am. Proc., 29: 566--572.  Frazee, C.G., Fehrenbacher, J.B. and Krumbein, W.C., 1970. Loess distribution from a  source. Soil Sci. Soc. Am. Proc., 34: 296--301.  Frye, J.C., Glass, H.D. and Wi